-- S. African Stocks: Anglo American, ArcelorMittal, Naspers, Sasol
-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a
-- 2011-02-03T16:11:56Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-03/south-african-equities-anglo-platinum-investec-naspers-sasol.html
South Africa’s FTSE/JSE Africa All
Share Index climbed to the highest level since May 2008,
advancing 307.23, or 1 percent, to 32,794.84 at the 5 p.m. close
in Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    Anglo American Plc  (AGL SJ), the diversified mining company
that makes up 10 percent of South Africa’s benchmark stock
index, rose for the fourth day, adding 1.6 percent, or 6.01
rand, to 381.51 rand. The mining company’s Collahuasi joint
venture was not affected by an electricity supply cut in Chile
overnight, spokeswoman Bernardita Fernandez said by e-mail.    BHP Billiton Plc  (BIL SJ), the world’s largest mining
company, rose to the highest level since June 2008, gaining 4.78
rand, or 1.7 percent, to 293.78 rand.  Optimum Coal Holdings 
Ltd., a South African producer of the fuel, may bid for
undeveloped coal reserves held by larger competitor  BHP Billiton
Ltd . as rising prices boost demand.    ArcelorMittal South Africa Ltd . (ACL SJ), the continent’s
largest steel-maker that recently bought Imperial Crown Trading,
jumped to the highest level since April 26, gaining 3.14 rand,
or 3.7 percent, to 89 rand. South Africa’s Department of Mineral
Resources rejected allegations that it has been biased in its
handling of a dispute over Sishen’s mining rights, which have
been won by Imperial Crown Trading, according to a statement
issued by the department today.    Central Rand Gold Ltd . (CRD SJ), a South African producer
of the metal, fell to the lowest level since December, dropping
29 percent to 25 cents. The company will delay some projects due
to lack of funding commitment by the government, according to a
regulatory statement.    Investec Plc  (INP SJ), a South African private bank and
wealth manager, rose for a third day, adding 56 cents, or 1
percent, to 56.91 rand. The company said its asset- and wealth-
management businesses have “benefitted from substiantial
inflows and good investment performance.”    Naspers Ltd . (NPN SJ), Africa’s biggest media company,
advanced the most since Nov. 18, adding 14.95 rand, or 3.9
percent to 400.95 rand. Macquarie Group Ltd. raised its rating
on Naspers to “outperform” from “neutral.”  Optimum Coal Holdings Ltd. (OPT SJ), the coal producer rose
for the second day in three, gaining 90 cents, or 2.7 percent,
to 33.90 rand. Optimum Coal said first-half profit rose to 274.6
million rand ($38 million) from 69.7 million rand.    Sasol Ltd . (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, advanced the most since Dec. 6, gaining 8.30
rand, or 2.4 percent to 360.95 rand. Oil rallied for a fifth day
in London as protests in Egypt turned violent, prompting concern
that crude supplies will be disrupted and unrest may spread to
other parts of the Middle East.  To contact the reporter on this story:
